<p>Cuba is rolling out urgent fuel rationing and contingency measures to keep electricity generation and other essential services running as a deepening shortage hits the island; authorities and state media blame US pressure aimed at cutting off oil supplies. The crunch is also rippling into regional politics, with Mexico signaling support for Cuba while weighing President Donald Trump’s threat of tariffs on countries that ship oil to Havana.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/CXlb2tTBw7hl7qFfA18UpmHDhY9QYCVDpK8bgcGiC3gvWZ3YLZgmwqLqkGYkE5WSNH3hmGAd7jfX1jYTrj4DLbWEglM9vwzRLTMfQGUaDnR881KVRfnpbzwSZdJgJuo4RSvnli0Fzt7OOnvCeJZmYujMFR4ua3rUib5BBZy80qWEEjA7d0uuHsH3G6iY633Yuog9WLTQRvlYAwY1setwn24e2MTvg4bTi-H6gr5-qx0oI26BvRYsgCp3' alt='A view from Cuba amid reported fuel shortages and energy rationing.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Life disruptions: Coverage describes Havana’s urban bus service largely grinding to a halt, hospitals preparing to scale back non-urgent care, and longer planned blackouts in some areas as fuel runs short.</li><li>Rationing focus: Cuban authorities said they will steer limited fuel supplies toward electricity generation, vital transport, and other essential public services.</li><li>Mexico’s dilemma: Sources cited in reporting said Mexican officials are looking for ways to get fuel to Cuba for basic needs like electricity and transportation while limiting the risk of US retaliation via tariffs.</li><li>Protest signals: Social-media posts cited in regional coverage describe pots-and-pans protests in parts of Havana as shortages and outages bite.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Cuban government: Officials blamed Washington for the fuel shortage and said rationing will prioritize essential services during the energy crisis. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/cuba-adopts-measures-to-confront-energy-crisis/a-75852484'>DW</a>)</li><li>Mexico (Sheinbaum administration): President Claudia Sheinbaum promised food support for Cuba and said Mexico is negotiating with the US after President Trump warned of tariffs on countries shipping oil to Havana. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/2/6/mexico-promises-food-support-for-cuba-as-us-stifles-the-islands-fuel-supply'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li><li>Mexican officials (sources): Officials are weighing ways to send fuel to Cuba for basic needs like electricity and transport while avoiding US reprisals, according to people familiar with the talks. (<a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/mexico-seeking-wayto-sendfuel-to-cuba-without-being-hit-by-us-tariffs-sources-say'>The Straits Times</a>)</li><li>DW expert analysis: A Latin America expert in Havana said the fuel crunch could be devastating for the economy and population if the oil embargo holds. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/us-oil-blockade-how-long-before-cuba-collapses/a-75849429'>DW</a>)</li><li>World Socialist Web Site: WSWS argued the Trump administration’s measures amount to an “energy blockade” meant to pressure Cuba’s government and risk a humanitarian “collapse.” (<a href='https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2026/02/07/kqhw-f07.html'>World Socialist Web Site</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/cuba-to-protect-essential-services-as-us-moves-to-cut-off-oil-supply'>Cuba to protect essential services as US moves to cut off oil supply</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/us-oil-blockade-how-long-before-cuba-collapses/a-75849429'>US oil blockade: How long before Cuba collapses?</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/cuba-adopts-urgent-measures-to-address-energy-crisis-minister/article70602843.ece'>Cuba adopts urgent measures to address energy crisis: Minister</a> - thehindu.com</li><li><a href='https://en.mercopress.com/2026/02/07/fuel-crunch-halts-havana-buses-squeezes-hospitals-and-deepens-cuba-s-power-cuts'>Fuel crunch halts Havana buses, squeezes hospitals and deepens Cuba’s power cuts</a> - 